<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
In typography, a <a title="Fixed Space" href="Fixed_Space">fixed space</a> having a height and a width equal to that of the <a title="Point Size" href="Point_Size">point size</a>. For example, in a 12-point <a title="Font" href="Font">font</a>, an <a title="Em Space" href="Em_Space">em space</a> is 12 points wide and 12 points high. An <a title="Em Dash" href="Em_Dash">em dash</a> is a <a title="dash" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/dash">dash</a> equal to the size of an em in a particular typeface at a particular size. An <a title="En" href="En">en</a> is defined as a fixed space half the size of the em. Thus, in 12-point type, an <a title="En Space" href="En_Space">en space</a> would be 6 points wide. (See <a title="Fixed Space" href="Fixed_Space">Fixed Space</a> and <a title="Dash" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/Dash">Dash</a>.) The em was originally defined as a square the size of a capital letter "M," which extends to the <a title="Descender" href="Descender">descender</a> line. This definition is no longer accurate. 
</p>
